data=data.table(read.csv("mcp_with_variables.csv"))

accu=function(actual,forecast){
  n=length(actual)
  error=actual-forecast
  mean=mean(actual)
  sd=sd(actual)
  CV=sd/mean
  MAPE=sum(abs(error/actual))/n
  l=data.frame(MAPE)
  return(l)
}

But result of adf test in dollar case is better than euro (Lower df value means more evidence to reject null hypothesis).So dollar data seems more stationary and dollar will be chosen as the currency for MCP for further analyses.

Autocorrelations of MCPs

acf(try,lag=300)

acf(dollar,lag=300)

acf(euro,lag=300)

As it is seen above, there is an obvious pattern in each acf plot of MCPs. High autocorrelation at lag1, lag2 ,lag3 (integer values of lag variable) tells us there is daily seasonality (Frequancy was 24 in each). Moreover, it can be also concluded that there is relatively high autocorrelation at lag 7 weekly seasonality in addition to daily seasonality. This means each same hour of different days has similarity and each same day of different weeks has similarity too. For example, monday values are close to each other and 12:00 values are close to each other. These seasonalities holds for 3 types of MCPs. ACF of Try has more autocorrelation which makes it less stationary, ACF of dollar has the least autocorrelation which makes it best option again, ACF of euro is somewhere in between try and dollar. As it is declared in previous part, we continue with dollar as mcp currency.

Step 3

In this step, a forecasting will be done with time series analysis.

Seasonality and Decomposition

Possibly type of seasonality is daily and weekly just as declared in the previous part.

Multiplicative and additive time series decomposition is utilized in this chapter.

As it is seen in the plot, additive method gives better random values with more stable variance and mean. Both type of decomposition have outliers but in the multiplicative one, random value which is obtained from deseasonalization and detrend is not preferable compared to additive one.

Below part shows how decomposition is carried out.

dec<-decompose(dollar,type = "additive")
deseasonalized<-dollar-dec$seasonal
ts.plot(deseasonalized)

detrend<-deseasonalized-dec$trend
ts.plot(detrend)

Arima and Sarima Models

Code given below tries 3 manuel and 1 auto arima models.And fit3 is the best option due to low BIC and AIC (It is also simpler than auto arima).

fit1=arima(dollar,order=c(1,0,0))
fit2=arima(diff(dollar,24),order=c(1,0,0))
fit3=arima(diff(dollar,24),order=c(1,0,0),seasonal=c(0,0,1))
arr=auto.arima(diff(dollar,24),max.p = 3,max.P = 1,max.q = 3,max.Q = 1,max.d = 1,max.D = 1)

As it is seen from residuals table, residuals have close distribution to normal, around 0 mean and stable variance except for outliers. However, auto correlation is still too much.

This is final and the best model by adding lag1 to decrease autocorrelation.

Obviously rg 5 is the best model because autocorrelation is the least in this model. Residual mean and variance are acceptable for assumptions and residuals histogram seems close to normal distribution. Also its r-square, p-value numbers are better than all the other models. P-values of independent variables tells us they are significant.

Conclusion

In this forecasting problem, 2 different methods has been utilised. According to MAPE values, regression model (MAPE=0.0542962) seems better than time series model (MAPE=0.1356153). In time series model, same trend value is used so it makes time series model less accurate. However, in regression model we could covered both seasonality and independent regressors succesfully in a better way.
